fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-104",
  description: "Predicate variables (?P) in rule bodies. Extend kernel beyond first-order Horn so a variable can occupy functor position. Required by auto-generated induction principles (proposal 025 §Auto-generated induction rules, lines 145-216). Deliverables: parser accepts ?P(args) in goal position; resolver routes predicate-variable functors through a separate symbol-kind path; pattern-fragment restriction enforced at load (Miller, lines 228-239) — predicate vars only in body position, args must be distinct first-order terms or variables, no nested predicate vars. Acceptance: a hand-written rule using ?P loads without error; pattern-fragment violations produce a clear load error. Prerequisite for WI-106 (kernel principle generation) and WI-101 (induction tactic). See proposal 025 §Auto-generated induction rules.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-029"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T10:31:05Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-105",
  description: "Nested implication (`-:`) inside `forall` in rule bodies. The hereditary-Harrop step-case form used by structural induction: (forall(?h, ?rest), ?P(?rest) -: ?P(cons(head: ?h, tail: ?rest))). Distinct from WI-027 (plain forall in rule bodies) — this adds the inner implication arrow that scopes the inductive hypothesis. Deliverables: tree-sitter grammar for `-:` inside forall body; parse IR node (NestedImpl{antecedents, consequent}); load.rs lowers it preserving De Bruijn scoping under the forall binder. Acceptance: hand-written rule with `(forall(?x), Q(?x) -: P(?x))` parses, loads, and round-trips. Prerequisite for WI-106 (kernel emits this form) and WI-108 (SLD resolves it).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-027", "WI-029"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T10:48:02Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-106",
  description: "Auto-generate <Sort>.cases / <Sort>.induction rules from sort/enum constructor structure during load. Generation rules (proposal 025 lines 205-209): for each entity constructor emit one case; fields of the entity's own sort type contribute induction hypotheses (`?P(?field)` premise under a forall binding the field); non-recursive fields are universally quantified; entities with no recursive fields are base cases. Examples in 025: Color.cases (finite enum), List.induction (single-recursion), Tree.induction (multi-recursion with two IHs). Implementation: kb/load.rs post-pass that walks each user-defined sort, synthesizes the induction Rule, registers it in the sort's scope under the qualified name `<sort_qname>.induction` (or `.cases` for non-recursive enums). Acceptance: loading a file with `enum List { entity nil entity cons(head: T, tail: List[T]) end }` produces a queryable rule List.induction whose body matches proposal 025 line 170-173. Prerequisite for WI-101 (consumer tactic).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-104", "WI-105"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T10:56:39Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-107",
  description: "Built-in numeric induction principles (Int.induction, BigInt.induction). Not derivable from constructor structure — kernel-emitted for primitive sorts at KB-init time. Forms (proposal 025 lines 189-203): `rule Int.induction(?P, ?lo, ?hi) :- ?P(?lo), (forall(?n), gte(?n, ?lo), lt(?n, ?hi), ?P(?n) -: ?P(add(?n, 1)))` (bounded well-founded); `rule BigInt.induction(?P) :- ?P(0), (forall(?n), gt(?n, 0), ?P(sub(?n, 1)) -: ?P(?n))` (strong induction). Headline driver: lf1 reachability proof (∀k ≥ 0. d_min ≤ d_k ≤ d_max) instantiates Int.induction with ?P = λk. d_min ≤ distance_at_step(k) ≤ d_max. Deliverables: hand-emitted rules in stdlib/anthill/prelude/int.anthill (or kernel synthesis if predicate-var literals can't be written by hand). Acceptance: lf1 safety_gps.anthill can reference Int.induction and the proof obligation reduces to base + step subgoals dischargeable by Z3.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test+discharge")],
  depends_on: ["WI-104", "WI-105"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T11:06:11Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-109",
  description: "Add Value::Var(Var) variant — a typed value-level representation of logic variables (flex / DeBruijn / rigid). Driver: makes the Term ↔ Value round-trip lossless for variable-bearing terms, and unblocks future stdlib tactics or proof primitives that manipulate partially-discharged proof states in eval-land. Today logic variables only exist as Term::Var via Value::Term(TermId); reflect encodes them lossily as Value::Entity{var_repr, name: '?name'|'_n'|'!name'} (string-prefix kind discrimination, no structural reconstruction). After this work item, the encoding becomes Value::Var(Var) — kind-typed, structurally roundtrippable. Surface area: ~83 Value::* match sites across 14 files (anthill-core/src/{eval,kb,persistence,reflect}, anthill-stl/src/reflect). Each site needs a Value::Var(_) arm with case-by-case semantics: structural_eq compares by Var equality; arithmetic / comparison ops error with clear 'cannot evaluate over a variable' message; term-conversion (alloc_from_value) routes to Term::Var; pattern matching may want to bind. NOT NEEDED for WI-108 alone (skolem-leakage invariant prevents Rigid reaching Value round-trips); no current driver. Open until a future tactic or stdlib op forces the issue. See docs/status/wi-108.md §'Var::Rigid at the Value level' for the constraint this work item lifts.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-108",
  description: "Phase 2.6b — nested-implication / forall resolution in the SLD evaluator. Use-time consumer of WI-105/106/107: when a rule body contains `(forall(?x), Q(?x) -: P(?x))` and the goal is P(?t), the resolver needs to discharge Q(?t) under the substitution ?x↦?t (introducing a fresh witness for the bound variable) rather than treat the implication opaquely. Pattern-fragment unification (Miller) for the predicate-variable case. Deliverables: kb/resolve.rs handles NestedImpl goals; eager universal instantiation when ?P is unified by the outer caller. Acceptance: a query against List.induction (WI-106) succeeds for a concretely-instantiated ?P; lf1 reachability proof terminates with `unsat` for both base and step subgoals. Required by WI-101 if the induction tactic dispatches sub-queries through the SLD evaluator rather than purely via SMT.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-106", "WI-107"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T11:54:07Z"))
fact Feedback(content: "Grammar: nested_implication rule added in tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js (line ~630), syntax (forall(?b1, ?b2, ...), antecedents -: consequent). Wired into _atom_term + is_term_kind. IR: convert_nested_implication in parse/convert.rs lowers to forall_impl(tuple(binders), tuple(antecedents), tuple(consequent)) using existing alloc_fn_term helper. Round-trip: TermPrinter special-cases forall_impl back to surface syntax (write_comma_sep helper, unwrap_tuple returning &[TermId]). 3 acceptance tests pass: nested_impl_in_rule_body_parses_and_loads, nested_impl_round_trips_through_printer, nested_impl_multi_binder_multi_antecedent. Full anthill-core suite green (124 tests, 0 regressions). Deferred to WI-108: proper inner-binder scoping at SLD resolution time.", at: "2026-04-27T10:48:03Z", workitem: "WI-105", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Recursive-position IH form added. emit_induction_rule classifies fields via field_is_recursive (Simple TypeExpr with remapped symbol equal to sort). Entities with recursive fields emit forall_impl(binders, IHs, [consequent]). Non-recursive ctors keep flat ho_apply. Test recursive_field_emits_inductive_hypothesis verifies for enum IntList. Printed form matches proposal 025. All 605 anthill-core tests pass. Parameterised sorts still skip emission upstream; covered by WI-107.", at: "2026-04-27T10:56:45Z", workitem: "WI-106", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Authored rule induction in stdlib/anthill/prelude/int.anthill and bigint.anthill (not via kernel synthesis — neither Int nor BigInt has constructor entities, so emit_induction_rule does not apply). Forms match proposal 025 lines 189-203 verbatim. Int.induction(?P, ?lo, ?hi) printed step: (forall(?n), gte(?n, ?lo), lt(?n, ?hi), ho_apply(?P, ?n) -: ho_apply(?P, add(?n, 1))). BigInt.induction(?P) uses sub(?n, 1) IH for strong induction. New numeric_induction_test.rs: 2 tests verifying body shape and forall_impl step. Pattern fragment check passes for stdlib (typing_test::pattern_fragment_stdlib_valid). Full workspace 756 tests, 0 failures.", at: "2026-04-27T11:06:11Z", workitem: "WI-107", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Hereditary Harrop discharge of forall_impl shipped through three tiers. (1) Var::Rigid(VarId) variant added (term.rs); appears only post-open. Synonyms documented (Skolem, eigenvariable). Storage-side variant (RigidDeBruijn) not added — no driver. (2) Frame gains assumed_facts: Vec<TermId>; inherited via clone on push. (3) step_init detects forall_impl by functor name, calls step_forall_impl which: walks binders/antecedents/consequent tuples, allocates fresh Var::Rigid for each binder, substitutes Global to Rigid via subst_globals helper, prepends skolemized consequents to goal stream, appends skolemized antecedents to assumed_facts. (4) Candidate gains Assumption(Substitution) variant; candidate gathering tries match_term against each frame's assumed_facts. (5) builtin_eq/neq updated: delay only on flex (Global), not Rigid — relies on hash-cons identity for Rigid==Rigid. Tier acceptance: t1 passthrough (was already free — resolver doesn't crash), t3 reflexivity, t3 unsoundness check (rigid cannot bind to concrete), t4 IH-as-assumption. 760 workspace tests, 0 regressions. Design doc at docs/status/wi-108.md. Open: Global~Rigid binding currently produces a normal subst entry (Global bound to Term::Var(Rigid)) — works for tested cases; revisit if it produces surprising solutions in stdlib induction proofs.", at: "2026-04-27T11:54:08Z", workitem: "WI-108", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Hardening pass: added 2 tests + 2 fixes. (1) Test t4_assumption_does_not_leak_to_next_body_goal — surrounding rule has body :- forall_impl(...), false_assumption. Without scoping, false_assumption would discharge against the leaked antecedent. Fix: __pop_assumption(N) synthetic marker emitted at the boundary between consequents and rest_of_body; step_init detects it and pops N from frame.assumed_facts. (2) Test structural_induction_proves_property_via_auto_generated_rule — exercises the full WI-106 induction rule end-to-end: enum IntList { i_nil; i_cons(head, tail) } + prop_holds defined inductively + query IntList.induction(prop_holds). Three fixes required: (a) emit_induction_rule (load.rs:2904) was using bare intern(\"ho_apply\") which produces a symbol disconnected from BuiltinTag::HoApply (registered against qualified anthill.reflect.Expr.ho_apply). Fix: look up by_qualified_name first; bare intern as fallback. Pre-existing bug, only surfaced now. (b) Antecedents pushed to assumed_facts must be lower_ho_apply'd at push-time so they share functor with the resolved-form lookup of the consequent's recursive call. (c) Goal must be reified through frame.subst before matching against assumed_facts (otherwise a flex var bound to a rigid won't compare equal to the assumption's rigid term). 6 WI-108 tests passing; 762 workspace tests, 0 regressions.", at: "2026-04-27T13:29:49Z", workitem: "WI-108", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Lifted the parameterised-sort exclusion in emit_induction_rule (the comment claimed cpp-gen collision, but cpp-gen only iterates rules via specific functor queries — Implementation/SortInfo/OperationInfo — and never enumerates <Sort>.induction symbols). Two related fixes: (1) emit_induction_rule now fires for any sort with constructors, including parametric ones. The rule body never references the type parameter, so polymorphism has no effect on shape. (2) Found a second bug: define() looks up by short_name in the scope's locals; all top-level enums share _global, so the first emit_induction_rule call would register 'induction → SymN' in _global.locals and subsequent calls would reuse SymN without inserting their qualified_name into by_qualified_name — making each <Sort>.induction except the first unreachable by qualified-name lookup. Fixed by scoping the induction symbol to the sort itself (sort_term.raw()) rather than parent_domain. New test structural_induction_on_stdlib_polymorphic_list exercises auto-generated anthill.prelude.List.induction(?P) end-to-end. Total: 7 WI-108 tests passing; 763 workspace tests, 0 regressions.", at: "2026-04-27T14:12:36Z", workitem: "WI-108", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Gap audit pass: probed 6 potential weaknesses with targeted tests; found 1 critical soundness bug. ROOT CAUSE: term_view.rs mapped Var::Rigid to ViewHead::Var, making the discrim tree treat skolems as flex wildcards. A goal 'pred(!rigid)' would falsely unify with a fact 'pred(concrete)' because the discrim's Var arm at line 420 calls collect_all_leaves(node) — gathering EVERY leaf under the current node, including concrete-key patterns. This produced unsound matches AND triggered combinatorial blow-up in multi-recursive structural induction (Tree with branch(left,right) hung indefinitely). FIX: map Var::Rigid to ViewHead::Opaque, which only matches patterns with var_edges (never concrete keys) and adds no substitution binding. New tests: gap_minimal_rigid_vs_fact_concrete_does_not_match, gap_minimal_rigid_vs_concrete_pattern_does_not_match (regression guards), gap_skolem_does_not_leak_into_caller_solution, gap_nested_forall_impl_in_consequent, gap_duplicate_binders_in_forall_impl, gap_multi_recursive_constructor_emits_multiple_ihs (Tree end-to-end). 13 WI-108 tests passing total; 769 workspace tests, 0 regressions.", at: "2026-04-27T15:09:16Z", workitem: "WI-108", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 1 cache shipped. Module: anthill-smt-gen/src/cache/{key,store,location,mod}.rs. Cache key: sha256 over emitted_smt_lib + tactic_canon + hint_qns + transitive rule_dep_hash + transitive fact_dep_hash + stdlib + z3_version + cache_format_version. Single-walk fold: walk_visited does both content-hash + functor collection in one pass. Two-layer guarantee verified by 6 cache_key unit tests (key.rs) including the depth-2 transitive-fact change scenario. CLI wiring: dispatch_z3 looks up before solver invocation, writes verdict after; flags --no-cache / --refresh-cache / --show-cache / --gc-cache <days> / --stats / --cache-dir. End-to-end tests (anthill-cli/tests/prove_cache_test.rs, 7 tests via real CLI + real Z3 + on-disk cache): cache_hit_on_second_run, cache_invalidates_on_transitive_fact_edit (the headline correctness guarantee against the live pipeline), no_cache_flag_bypasses_lookup_and_write, refresh_cache_forces_resolver_rerun_then_writes, show_cache_lists_entries, gc_cache_removes_old_entries, stats_flag_prints_hit_miss_summary. Workspace 785 tests, 0 failures. Remaining: discharge.sh second-run-fast (<600ms) acceptance benchmark; deferred until lf1 proofs are stable.", at: "2026-04-27T16:37:18Z", workitem: "WI-096", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 2 grammar+IR shipped. The grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js) already accepted tactic terms as nested fn_terms via _fn_arg → _term → fn_term — no grammar changes needed. The deliverable was the typed Tactic IR + converter. Added to parse/ir.rs: enum Tactic { Bare(Symbol), App(Symbol, Vec<TacticArg>), Raw(String), Mapping(MappingBlock) } with TacticArg { name: Option<Symbol>, value: TacticArgValue } and TacticArgValue { Tactic, String, Int, Bool, Name }. ProofStrategy gains tactic: Option<Tactic>; legacy args: Vec<TermId> retained for anthill-cli backwards compat. convert.rs: convert_tactic_fn_term + convert_tactic_named_arg + convert_tactic_term_node lift the existing parsed terms into the typed IR. Backwards-compat: 'by z3(logic: \"LRA\")' desugars to 'by z3(tactic: smt(logic: \"LRA\"))' — same App(\"smt\", [logic: LRA]) as the explicit form. Tests (anthill-core/tests/tactic_ir_test.rs, 9 tests): legacy_z3_logic_arg_lifts_to_smt_application (the desugaring anchor), explicit_smt_tactic_named_arg, then_combinator_with_two_bare_tactics, or_else_with_nested_smt_apps, raw_escape_carries_string_payload, induction_meta_tactic_with_over_and_step, non_z3_strategy_has_no_tactic_ir, legacy_args_field_still_populated, lf1_existing_proofs_parse_unchanged. Workspace 794 tests, 0 regressions. The Tactic IR is now consumable by Phase 3 (pass-through emit), Phase 4 (outcome layer), Phase 5 (ranking), Phase 6 (induction).", at: "2026-04-27T17:01:56Z", workitem: "WI-097", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 3 pass-through tactic emit shipped. Module: anthill-smt-gen/src/tactic_emit.rs. Two API entry points: emit_tactic_expr (parse-side, walks Tactic IR from WI-097) and emit_tactic_from_term (CLI-side, walks runtime KB Term::Fn). Both produce the body of (check-sat-using ...) — Bare/App/Raw lower to Z3 syntax: smt → 'smt' or '(using-params smt :random_seed 42)'; then/or_else/par → '(then a b)'/'(or-else a b)'/'(par-or a b)' (anthill→Z3 keyword translation); repeat(t, times: 5) → '(repeat t 5)'; raw('...') splices verbatim. Trivial-default elision: bare smt with only logic/timeout returns None → caller emits plain (check-sat) (preserves the lf1 byte-stream + cache hits). Combinator children DON'T elide — emit_term_force/emit_tactic_force always produce a string so 'then(simplify, smt)' becomes '(then simplify smt)'. ProofConfig.tactic_expr threads the rendered string through render_satisfiability_with + render_upper_bound_with: when Some(expr), close with (check-sat-using <expr>); when None, plain (check-sat). CLI dispatch_z3 reads the runtime ProofRecord's args, looks for 'tactic:' named arg, walks the value term via emit_tactic_from_term. Pre-existing bug fixed: read_named_arg's syms.named_arg cache returned None for bare-interned 'named_arg', causing tool_args to silently empty; now also matches by short-name suffix. ArgValue gained Term(TermId) variant so non-primitive named-arg values flow through. Tests: 9 unit (parse-side) + 6 E2E (real CLI + dry-run, including legacy_lf1_proofs_unchanged anchor). Workspace 809 tests, 0 regressions.", at: "2026-04-27T19:32:01Z", workitem: "WI-098", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 4 outcome layer shipped. ProofConfig gains produce_models / produce_unsat_cores / produce_interpolants. Renderers (render_satisfiability_with + render_upper_bound_with) emit (set-option :produce-* true) before (set-logic ...), (get-model) / (get-unsat-core) after (check-sat-using ...). Z3 output parsed by anthill-smt-gen/src/outcome.rs (parse_z3_output → OutcomeData with verdict, model_text, variable_assignments, unsat_core, interpolants_text). Balanced-paren splitter handles nested (model (define-fun ...)) blocks; tolerant of negative values, whitespace, malformed input. CacheEntry extended (#[serde(default)] non-breaking) with model_text, variable_assignments, unsat_core. dispatch_z3 reads model: / cores: / interpolation: tactic args (added ArgValue::Bool variant; bool_of helper handles String/Int/Bool), threads through ProofConfig, parses outcome from Z3 stdout, populates cache entry, prints model bindings + unsat-core in verbose mode. Tests: 7 unit (outcome::tests) + 5 E2E (prove_outcome_test) including cache_entry_carries_model_text which exercises the full pipeline with real CLI + Z3 + on-disk JSON. Workspace 821 tests, 0 regressions. Deferred to follow-up: registering ProofCounterexample / ProofCore as kernel fact schemas in load.rs (currently the outcome data lives in the cache entry; user-level fact-assertion is a smaller WI on top). interpolants emit is wired flag-only — get-interpolants requires named (assert! ... :named ...) which the current emitter doesn't produce.", at: "2026-04-27T20:28:24Z", workitem: "WI-099", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 5 ranking meta-tactic shipped (minimum-viable form). Surface: ranking(boundedness: <rule_qn>, decrease: <rule_qn>) — user supplies two pre-written obligation rules; tactic dispatches each as a sub-query through the standard SMT path (run_smt_subquery extracted from dispatch_z3) and combines verdicts: both unsat → Proved; either sat → Disproved with the failing sub-query name; either unknown → Unknown. Sub-queries inherit base config (logic, timeout, model/cores flags) but get tactic_expr: None so they emit plain (check-sat). Each sub-query goes through the cache + outcome plumbing independently — Phase 1/4 compose with no special-casing. Architectural pattern (multi-subquery dispatch, run_smt_subquery helper) is the same shape WI-101 (induction tactic) needs and reuses. Not delivered: building the SMT queries automatically from a measure: function (Path A in the workitem); user writes the two violation rules instead. The lf1 transponder migration (replace PostArmedExcursionBound fact + delete the manual ranking test) is deferred — needs the user-supplied measure path to be ergonomic. Two E2E tests in prove_ranking_test.rs: ranking_with_both_subqueries_unsat_proves; ranking_with_failing_decrease_disproves. Workspace 823 tests, 0 regressions.", at: "2026-04-27T21:04:00Z", workitem: "WI-100", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 6 induction meta-tactic shipped (minimum-viable form). Surface options: (a) numeric/binary form 'induction(over: <sort>, base: <base_rule>, step: <step_rule>)' for Int.induction-shaped proofs (1 base + 1 step); (b) multi-case form 'induction(case1, case2, ..., caseN)' for arbitrary-arity case splits. Detected by recognise_induction_tactic alongside ranking; dispatched via dispatch_induction which calls run_smt_subquery for each case (reusing WI-100's helper). Verdicts combine identically: all proved → Proved; first disproved → Disproved with case name; first unknown → Unknown. The 'over:' arg is consumed for diagnostics only — the SMT layer doesn't synthesize quantified obligations from the sort definition; the user supplies pre-shaped arithmetic obligation rules per case (the SLD-side discharge of <Sort>.induction with predicate variables lives in WI-108; this Z3-side path complements it for arithmetic claims that don't fit the SLD evaluator). Three E2E tests in prove_induction_test.rs: induction_with_base_and_step_proved_combines_to_proved, induction_with_failing_step_disproves, induction_dispatches_three_positional_cases. Workspace 826 tests, 0 regressions. Not delivered: auto-synthesizing the per-case obligations from the user's measure/predicate (would replace user-written violation rules with auto-generated ones from a single property statement). Lf1 reachability migration (proof reachability_holds by z3(tactic: induction(over: Int, base: lf1_base_violation, step: lf1_step_violation))) requires writing the two arithmetic violation rules in safety_gps.anthill — separate work item to land them properly.", at: "2026-04-28T04:06:54Z", workitem: "WI-101", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-110",
  description: "Audit anthill-core tests that may rely on tree-sitter's permissive error recovery. Background: ho_bigint_induction_parses (typing_test.rs) used a malformed source — '-:' inside a fn-term arg with no grammar rule for that position — and was passing only because tree-sitter embedded the ERROR node inside an fn_term and the Rust parse::parse only flags top-level ERROR nodes. WI-C1's '-:' rule-conclusion clause exposed the bug by promoting the ERROR to top-level. Sweep: grep for tests that call parse::parse with .is_ok() asserts but never check the resulting tree for embedded ERROR nodes; tighten parse::parse to surface embedded errors OR fix test sources to use grammar-supported shapes. Acceptance: identify and either fix or document each test that depends on permissive recovery.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-111",
  description: "Proposal 030 phase α.1 — ProofWitness schema. Declare ProofWitness sort with constructors SmtDischarge, SldDerivation, MetaCompose, ScopeAxiom (with scope_kind/scope_qn/aspect fields), Specialization (with parametric/substitution/instances), TrustedAxiom; plus SmtVerdict, SortBinding, MetaTacticContract entities, in stdlib/anthill/realization/witness.anthill (new file). Loader updates to recognize the new sorts. Schema stable across all phases. See docs/proposals/030-theorem-registry.md §Schema additions.",
