  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-28T18:56:08Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-141",
  description: "WI-139 follow-up: [hint] SMT-side auto-include semantics. Per the brainstorm: rules tagged [hint] are auto-cited from any proof in the same enclosing scope chain — the SMT-side analogue of [simp]'s SLD-side auto-application. Implementation: new hint_cites_for(rule_qn, kb) in prove.rs walks all rules with hint flag in meta; for each, gets its head functor's QN and adds to effective using list iff the QN is prefixed by one of rule_qn's parent scope segments. v0 limitation: relies on lift_rule_to_implication_clause's QN-based lookup, which picks the first rule under the head functor — works for unique-head rules (definitional unfolds, top-level rules where label==head-functor) but breaks for shared-head equational rules. Per-RuleId lift helper for safety on shared functors deferred. Acceptance: cargo-test passes; new test verifies a [hint] rule is auto-applied to a sibling proof without explicit using.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-28T19:02:18Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-142",
  description: "Proposal 032 — scaland mirror port. The rustland implementation of the symmetric-arrow rule grammar (proposal 032) is in. Port the same change to scaland/. Surface area: (a) parser (fastparse) — replace dual-arrow rule production with the choice over (heads :- body | body -: heads | heads); add multi-head rule_heads with comma-separated terms; (b) parse IR — replace head/conclusion fields with heads: Vec; (c) loader — apply the same transitional translation as rustland: labeled non-equational positive rules synthesize a 0-arg label-functor as the KB head with user heads in conclusion; labeled equational rules keep the head-as-identity; labeled denial uses synthesized label-functor; unlabeled multi-head is rejected with a clear error. Acceptance: sbt test green; reference implementation parses the same .anthill files (stdlib, examples) as rustland. Delivered: scaland's KB has no `conclusion` field, so the rust translation collapses to the literal conjunctive expansion — labeled multi-head rules emit N horn rules sharing one body and var-scope; unlabeled multi-head is rejected with a clear error; bare-head facts and the `body -: heads` reverse arrow form both supported. stdlib/anthill/geometry.anthill (post-032) parses end-to-end.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-09T15:29:59Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-143",
  description: "Proposal 032 — smt-gen migration to unified head-as-conclusion encoding. Today the rustland loader keeps a transitional shape: labeled non-equational positive rules synthesize a 0-arg label-functor as the KB head and place the user-written head term(s) in 'conclusion'. The legacy assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion path stays alive only to keep smt-gen working without modification. Migration: rewrite smt-gen's collect_rule (anthill-smt-gen/src/lib.rs ~line 290) to use the rule head AS the conclusion when the head is positive (run it through process_body_goal and route into conclusion_assertions); when head is Bottom, conclusion_assertions stays empty (denial form). Drop the result_var extraction from the head's pos_args (the synthetic-label-with-result-var pattern goes away under 032). Once smt-gen runs on the unified encoding: simplify the loader to assert_rule_debruijn(head, body) without a conclusion vec. Acceptance: cargo test green; lift_implication_test exercises the new encoding; lf1 step_distance_lemma proof still discharges the same way.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-09T19:19:21Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-144",
  description: "Proposal 032 — drop legacy 'conclusion' KB field after smt-gen migration. Once WI-143 lands, the kb/mod.rs RuleEntry.conclusion: Vec<TermId> field, the rule_conclusion(rid) accessor, and the assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion helper are all dead code. Cleanup: (a) remove the conclusion field from RuleEntry; (b) remove rule_conclusion getter; (c) collapse assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion back into assert_rule_debruijn; (d) simplify the loader's load_rule (kb/load.rs ~line 3918) to call assert_rule_debruijn directly without manufacturing an empty conclusion. Also reconsider the loader's transitional translation: now that smt-gen consumes head-as-conclusion natively, labeled non-equational rules can use the user's head directly as the KB head (no synthesized 0-arg label functor), provided the citation gate is rewritten to look up by label rather than head functor. That citation gate refactor is a sibling work item — see comments in load.rs load_rule for context. Acceptance: cargo test green; the conclusion field has zero references in the workspace.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-143"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-145",
  description: "Proposal 032 — citation by label, not head functor. Under proposal 032 the head IS the rule's conclusion (e.g. 'gte(?x, 3.0)'); head functors are no longer unique rule identifiers, since many rules can share the same head functor (every positive arithmetic theorem has 'gte'/'lte' etc. as its head). The rule's identity for cite-resolution must therefore be the LABEL, not the head functor. Today's transitional load (rustland) papers over this by synthesizing a 0-arg label-functor as the KB head, but that's not the right architecture long-term: it forces an artificial KB term and prevents downstream code from using the head as the actual semantic claim. Migration: (a) cite-resolution (anthill-cli/src/prove.rs and any 'using' lookup paths) consults a label→rule map keyed on the rule's label, falling back to head functor only for unlabeled legacy rules; (b) by_functor index for SLD continues to use head functor (multi-rule per functor is fine for SLD); (c) loader stops synthesizing the label-functor head — labeled rules use the user's head term as the KB head directly. Depends on WI-143 (smt-gen migration). Acceptance: cargo test green; multi-head labeled rules work end-to-end; lf1 reachability_band cites work without the synthesized-functor workaround.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-143"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-146",
  description: "Proposal 031 phase b — dispatch_structured implementation. Phase a (grammar + IR + KB encoding) is done. Today the dispatcher recognizes ProofBodyStructured bodies and emits a clear Skipped verdict. Phase b iterates the steps and discharges each, then discharges the concluding clause. Surface area: (1) new dispatch_structured in anthill-cli/src/prove.rs that decodes the body term (read steps cons-list and conclude term), iterates steps, dispatches each steps tactic, accumulates step heads as hypotheses for subsequent dispatches; (2) hypothesis splicing — either synthesize transient KB rules for each step (so the existing using cite-resolution path picks them up via lift_rule_to_implication_clause) or extend ProofConfig.assumptions with extra inline assertions rendered from step head terms; (3) the concluding clauses using list is augmented with all step labels and dispatched against the parent rules claim; (4) wrap all sub-witnesses in MetaCompose with tactic_name=structured; (5) trust + cite propagation flows through MetaCompose beta-6 / gamma-1 unchanged. Test plan: small end-to-end test where a 3-step structured proof discharges each step via z3 and the concluding clause via z3-citing-all-steps; lf1 step_distance_lemma migrated from by trust to a structured proof per proposal 031 worked example, verifying the trust report shows the named step trusts (h4 scalar norm homogeneity, h6 velocity envelope) instead of one opaque lemma.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-143"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-29T05:48:22Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-147",
  description: "smt-gen: emit anthill_abs define-fun for SMT-LIB scripts that mention abs(). SMT-LIB has no built-in abs for Real; cited-rule lifts and direct discharges that touch abs (e.g. |d_next - d_prev| in lf1 step_distance_lemma) currently emit raw (abs ...) which Z3 treats as an uninterpreted Function. Surface area: in anthill-smt-gen process_body_goal, detect abs-functor calls (qualified name anthill.prelude.Numeric.abs or short-form abs); record a uses_abs flag on the Emitter; when rendering the final SMT script (render_satisfiability_with / lift_rule_to_implication_clause emit prelude), if uses_abs prepend (define-fun anthill_abs ((x Real)) Real (ite (< x 0) (- x) x)) and rewrite all (abs ...) call sites to (anthill_abs ...). Acceptance: lf1 step_distance_lemma h_geometric lifts with valid abs interpretation; cargo test green. Unblocks: WI-148, WI-149.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-29T06:51:10Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-148",
  description: "Variable-scope alignment for structured-proof steps. Today each step rule in a structured proof body has its own de Bruijn variable scope (convert_proof_step calls reset_var_scope). Result: a step head like `lte(?d_next, ?delta)` gets ?d_next ↦ var_0, ?delta ↦ var_1 in the steps scope, while the parent rule has its own scope where ?d_next ↦ var_X. The steps cited-lift then quantifies var_0/var_1 universally over Real, producing a vacuous forall axiom (e.g. forall (var_0 var_1 Real) ⇒ <= var_1 var_0) which is logically false. Fix: thread the parent rules var_map into convert_proof_step instead of resetting; step heads/bodies share the parents synthetic var_<i> names. Surface area: parse/convert.rs convert_proof_step removes reset_var_scope; load.rs encode_proof_step renders heads/bodies under the parents var scope; the loaders structured-body load arm passes the parents var_map down. Acceptance: lf1 step_distance_lemma h_geometric and h_envelope lift to forall axioms whose variables actually correspond to the parents distance/velocity vars, so the conclude clause by z3(logic: LRA) closes the chain. Depends on WI-147 (abs interpretation) for the lf1 case.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-147"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-29T07:33:27Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-149",
  description: "smt-gen: AbstractLift mode for cited-rule body rendering. When lifting a cited rule for use as a forall axiom in a consumers SMT preamble, smt-gen process_body_goal recursively unfolds entity destructures and chains through related rules, including grounding against fact data. Concretely: lf1 step_distance_lemmas body references distance_at_step, which expands transitively into position_distance_sq, which produces nonlinear var*var assertions plus ground constants from real_pose_at facts (e.g. (= (* var_3 var_3) 16.0) appearing in an LRA script). For a universal lemma about abstract distances, ground pose data is irrelevant and the nonlinearity blocks LRA discharge. Fix: add RenderMode { Discharge, AbstractLift } parameter to Emitter; in AbstractLift mode, process_body_goal stops at uninterpreted-predicate boundaries (does not chase entity destructures or rule expansions for predicates that arent already arithmetic). Calls from lift_rule_to_implication_clause use AbstractLift; calls from emit_satisfiability_check_with_deps use Discharge (existing behavior). Acceptance: cited rule lifts produce only the abstract claim (head plus minimal body needed to bind free vars); lf1 conclude with by z3(logic: LRA) closes once WI-147 + WI-148 also land.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-147"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-29T08:24:35Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-150",
  description: "WI-148 phase 2: loader-side var-scope alignment for structured-proof step synthesis. Phase 1 of WI-148 (committed) made parse-IR converter share VarIds between parent rules and structured-proof steps via a snapshot mechanism (rule_var_scopes keyed by label). However the alignment is a no-op for SMT discharge because the KB stores rules with `Var::DeBruijn(u32)` after `assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion` reindexes variables fresh per rule — the parents pre-DeBruijn Global VarIds are lost. Step rules synthesized in dispatch_structure are still independently DeBruijn-indexed; cited-rule lifts forall-quantify over fresh `var_<i>` names that dont link to the parents preamble declarations. Phase 2 surface area: (1) save the pre-DeBruijn VarIds list per rule at load time (extend RuleEntry in kb/mod.rs with `globals: Vec<VarId>` populated by assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion before reindexing). (2) Add `pub fn rule_globals(rid) -> &[VarId]` accessor. (3) In dispatch_structureds synthesize_step_rule, look up parents globals; pre-translate the steps head_term to use parent indices for shared vars, appending fresh ones for any step-introduced variables; assert via a new `assert_rule_debruijn_in_frame(globals, head, body, conclusion, ...)` API that takes a pre-computed vars list instead of recomputing. Acceptance: lf1 step_distance_lemma h_envelope cited lift produces `(<= var_X var_Y)` referencing PARENTS var indices (or a forall over only the step-introduced extras), not a vacuous self-contained universal. Combined with WI-147 + WI-149 the conclude clause flips to `by z3(logic: LRA)` and lf1 trust surface drops from 3 named trusts to 2 (h_geometric + h_envelope only).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-148"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-29T08:13:25Z"))

-- ── scaland resync (post-2026-03-21 catch-up). WI-142 was the first
-- ── scaland item under this umbrella; the items below carve up the
-- ── remaining gap into independently-shippable pieces.

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-151",
  description: "Parent / tracker — scaland resync to rustland's post-2026-03-21 surface. Umbrella covering proposals 025, 026, 030, 031, plus the WI-137/138/139/140/141/147/148/149/150 stack. Subdivided into WI-152 (proposals 025+031 grammar surface), WI-153 (stdlib/prelude alignment), WI-154 (rule attribute flags), WI-155 (witness schema KB-side loading), WI-156 (expression evaluator), WI-157 (anthill prove/check + witness checking), WI-158 (codegen). Closed when all children are Delivered or explicitly deferred. Scope intentionally excludes anything that would require redesigning scaland's KB schema beyond what the child WIs spell out — scaland remains a reference parser + loader + lightweight resolver, not a full prove/check pipeline.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-142"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-152",
  description: "scaland resync — proposals 025 + 031: proof / lemma / provides / structured-proof grammar. Add parser + IR support for `proof X by <tactic> end`, structured `proof X ... end` blocks (inner step rules + concluding `[using ...] by <tactic>` clause), `lemma` colocation block, `provides` block, and the `enum` keyword. Loader stores these as opaque KB facts; no witness checking, no proof discharge (those land in WI-157). Mirror references: tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js (proof / provides / enum / lemma productions); rustland/anthill-core/src/parse/ir.rs (ProofBody::SingleTactic / Structured, ProofStep). Scaland-side targets: scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/parse/AnthillParser.scala (new productions), parse/IR.scala (ProofBody, ProofStep types), load/Loader.scala (opaque KB encoding — witness/state_hash fields default). Acceptance: sbt test green; ParserIntegrationTest cases parsing one structured-proof example from examples/webots-modelling/lf1/ plus stdlib/anthill/realization/witness.anthill.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-142"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-02T09:07:33Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-153",
  description: "scaland resync — stdlib / Prelude alignment. Make Scala's prelude + source-resolver aware of new stdlib files: stdlib/anthill/prelude/algebra.anthill (Ring, VectorSpace per WI-138); stdlib/anthill/geometry.anthill (Vec3 + algebraic-law rules per WI-137 — already parses post-WI-142 but not yet loaded by Prelude); stdlib/anthill/realization/witness.anthill (ProofWitness, SmtVerdict, SortBinding entities — registration only, no checking); stdlib/anthill/prelude/float.anthill (abs, sqrt, sin, cos, etc.). Recommendation: load via SourceResolver as ordinary .anthill files at startup, not embedded in Prelude.scala (parallel to how rustland's stdlib_embedded.rs handles these). Files: scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/load/Prelude.scala, load/SourceResolver.scala. Acceptance: sbt test green; new ParserIntegrationTest cases load each of the four stdlib files end-to-end and assert sort/entity/rule counts.",
